# CLI Comprehension

Durable feature maps live in `docs/comprehension/`.

Current adapter boundary:

- The CLI owns portable cache/proxy behavior: adapter env vars, cache flags, proxy refs, on-disk adapter cache config, tag/ref planning, and local diagnostics that should work on a laptop, CI runner, or container.
- GitHub Actions owns runner orchestration: CLI installation, action outputs/state, detached proxy lifecycle, runtime/toolchain bootstrap, and GitHub-specific policy.
- BuildKit is a first-class CLI adapter through `boringcache buildkit`; it shares Docker's OCI cache plan and injects `buildctl build` cache refs without owning buildctl installation or daemon lifecycle.
- The Docker/BuildKit registry E2E keeps the existing `docker buildx` proof and, when `buildctl` can reach the temporary BuildKit builder, also runs a native `boringcache buildkit -- buildctl build` cold/warm smoke against the same Rails-backed workspace.
- `boringcache sccache` owns WebDAV env wiring and prints a best-effort `sccache --show-stats` summary after the wrapped command; it only supplies `CC`/`CXX` wrappers when the caller has not already exported those variables. sccache installation and server lifecycle stay caller-owned.
- `boringcache turbo` and `boringcache nx` detect npm/pnpm/yarn from `package.json` and lockfiles and inject the package-manager cache env from the CLI built-in entries. Corepack/runtime bootstrap stays outside the CLI.
- The GitHub action may separately read native `sccache --show-stats` when it owns split restore/save server lifecycle and action outputs; that is workflow diagnostics, not a second adapter env/tag/setup path. Add a CLI structured diagnostics surface before giving other adapters action-side cache-stat parsers.
- Docker/BuildKit GitHub Actions uses one standard alias family: default-branch runs read/write `default`, non-default branches read `branch-*` then `default` and write `branch-*`, and PR writes promote only `pr-*` when allowed. Local runs without CI metadata keep the single legacy `buildcache` ref.
- Docker/OCI manifest import is the one normal read path that asks Rails for live descriptor storage validation. BuildKit treats an imported manifest as all-or-nothing and cannot recover from a descriptor that Rails advertised but object storage no longer serves. Native remote-cache adapters keep the DB-trusted verified URL path so Bazel, sccache, Gradle, Maven, Nx, Turbo, and Go do not pay broad object HEAD checks on hot reads.
- Benchmark cache-eligibility is a shared contract, not a CLI-only verdict. The CLI/action side should emit expected cache inputs, restore/check outcomes, native hit-rate summaries, runner headroom, and run identity; Rails supplies lifecycle truth such as storage-limit eviction, and benchmark artifacts decide same-commit pairing plus `sample_valid`/`reporting_mode` before a row becomes a regression.
- Proxy stderr is quiet by default for userland and benchmark runs: one startup line, warnings/errors, and one shutdown summary. Detailed prefetch, refresh, blob upload, flush, and per-session lines require global `--verbose`, `BORINGCACHE_PROXY_DEBUG=1`, or debug-level logging.
- Disk-backed proxy startup remains warm-first by default. On GitHub Actions the startup prefetch governor picks a blob-shape profile: Bazel-style many-tiny CAS tags can start near the 2,000-read ceiling instead of ramping from a low warmup; Zed/sccache-style many-medium tags get a larger byte-budgeted prefetch window and start at that cap so several thousand multi-MiB blobs do not trickle through a 20-worker ramp; larger many-small, ordinary medium, and large blobs stay bounded by lower in-flight byte budgets. Startup prewarm uses that profile as its object-download gate instead of also waiting behind the generic on-demand download semaphore. Native remote-cache adapters get high throughput without benchmark-only env overrides, and Docker/OCI keeps its metadata-first body-on-demand path unless a diagnostic hydration mode asks otherwise.
- Proxy KV publish is two-phase for native remote-cache adapters. Background flushes upload ready CAS checkpoint entries under a hidden registry-root checkpoint tag so the runner can shed local spool data, but they do not move the stable registry/human tag. Shutdown promotes the latest complete checkpoint to the stable tag only after pending writes are drained. `upload in progress` is retryable contention, not a successful loser outcome; pending KV batches are restored and retried until publish succeeds or shutdown reaches its deadline. Permanent server 4xx responses during stable promotion, including `cache_entry must be pending or ready`, fail fast instead of being retried as transient publish contention. With `--fail-on-cache-error`, leftover pending writes or an unpromoted checkpoint make proxy shutdown fail so CI does not silently leave users on an earlier partial snapshot.
- Blob staging is deliberately smaller than blob download URL resolution. Downloads/prewarm can ask for large batches because they are read-only and latency-sensitive; upload staging is control-plane publish work, so the CLI uses smaller batches. Edge-generated HTML 400 responses from blob URL-planning endpoints (`/caches/blobs/stage` and `/caches/blobs/download-urls`) are transient transport failures; Rails JSON 4xx validation errors remain permanent. This keeps Bazel/sccache-style KV publish robust without hiding malformed client requests.
- Direct save treats unresolved pending uploads the same way across archive, file CAS, OCI CAS, and Bazel/file CAS layouts: non-strict saves can defer without counting the cache as saved, while `--fail-on-cache-error` fails if the command cannot publish or resume a ready entry. `run` inherits this through the shared save command. `mount` does not count saves, but archive and CAS sync now wait for a pending same-root publish to become visible through the normal restore path instead of treating pending as already synced.
- Direct archive transport has its own transfer profile, separate from proxy/CAS blob prefetch. Large archive restores probe that the signed URL really honors `Range` before writing ranged parts; if storage does not return `206 Partial Content`, restore falls back to one streaming download instead of risking corrupted byte placement. Archive save, restore, and mount share the same archive upload/download plan, expose `BORINGCACHE_ARCHIVE_DOWNLOAD_CONCURRENCY`, `BORINGCACHE_ARCHIVE_UPLOAD_CONCURRENCY`, and `BORINGCACHE_ARCHIVE_PARALLEL_DOWNLOAD_THRESHOLD_MB` as expert overrides, and send part count, part size, concurrency, and streaming/parallel shape through CLI metrics so web can explain archive transfer slowness separately from native adapter hit/miss health.
- Proxy session metadata is product-owned where possible: proxy startup attaches the resolved primary cache tag as `cache_tag`, or a stable `cache_scope` hash when the tag is too long/noisy, so web already-seen miss reporting can separate cache targets without asking users to label cold/warm phases.
- Proxy run identity is generic across CI and local dev. CI uses provider-neutral `BORINGCACHE_CI_*`/GitHub fields; non-CI proxy summaries detect the local git worktree when present and send repository leaf, branch/tag, and commit alongside the local run id. Directories without git stay `source_ref_type=local`.
- The Rust `target` built-in and `boringcache sccache` adapter own `CARGO_INCREMENTAL=0` as cache hygiene. The action can still set Cargo home/color and sccache cache size as runtime ergonomics.
- Cache list/inspect output distinguishes stored bytes from payload bytes. Archive entries can report true uncompressed size; CAS/proxy entries may only know blob payload bytes, so human output uses the stored byte count as payload instead of showing a misleading missing uncompressed value.
